Imagine You're Playing a Game

They Both Want to Talk to the Same Friend
Pat and Danny both say: ‚ÄúWe want our friend Alex to tell what happened.‚Äù

That‚Äôs totally fine!

But...

Who talks to Alex first?

Usually, whoever needs Alex to help their side first (maybe Pat).

Then the other kid gets to ask Alex questions after (that‚Äôs like cross-examination).

Should We Decide This Before the Game Starts?
YES. It's a good idea to plan things out a little:

Who will talk to Alex first?

Is Alex going to talk one time for both sides?

Or maybe come back and talk again later?

This helps everyone play fair and not waste time.

Simple Rule You Can Use:
If both Pat and Danny want to use the same friend (Alex), we could say:

‚ÄúWhoever is telling their story first gets to ask Alex questions first.‚Äù

That way, it‚Äôs fair. And the teacher (judge) can help make sure Alex doesn't just repeat everything.
